<subSubSection id="EFB8614154F5E85A85EA21736195902E" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="624F001C9DC053FFCF100B8AFA63B960" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D905A5CA028814BDA3A51CD7AD8E189" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName id="5A24E012077F6BD8CA262E1BE9369D44" baseAuthorityName="Schroeder" baseAuthorityYear="1956" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Leptolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptolepis curvisulcatus" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="BCE34960DA9506546A4E73BFADBE4F50" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptolepis curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly more elongate than 
<taxonomicName id="E6957B9C4DEF3F1CFE5B8704CB97C0A7" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. normandica" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="normandica">
<emphasis id="6E5E5AC6E2616CEA4A0EACC2BA4D5671" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. normandica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with an OL:OH ratio of 1.4-1.6 (vs. 1.25-1.45), which is mainly caused by a relatively low postdorsal rim, which is also more rounded. Other proportions and characteristics are shared with 
<taxonomicName id="8CF6D87D3867B9A5E71D0F99D4D29AFF" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. normandica" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="normandica">
<emphasis id="7707AF6F3723B3A365398051CA88F0AD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. normandica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="E916DEF971301346BD378775136D7074" baseAuthorityName="Schroeder" baseAuthorityYear="1956" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Leptolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leptolepis curvisulcatus" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="82175AF3B87F0D7ADE7E533F72106A37" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Leptolepis curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="842AD35B7716E5144D488E5B25C88E32" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. normandica" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="normandica">
<emphasis id="0CF872DABB688DB7A6230E0EFEEC8AAF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. normandica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its longer ostium as compared to the length of its cauda, but because of the gradual transition from ostium to cauda, this feature cannot be measured unequivocally. The rounded and short postdorsal rim distinguishes 
<taxonomicName id="074AA34A68B1674C906D2D30288C3CF8" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. curvisulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="1381B2BE45377A996868A8AE13BD286E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the coeval 
<taxonomicName id="D6FEE825E0BEEC403DDC63F9C624C09E" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. kremmeldorfensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kremmeldorfensis">
<emphasis id="0539356237B93D0054E71B3642EC28C9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. kremmeldorfensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="839CC2CBEE446D193EF8339B2ADD6D63" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="97B31E5B636C183FD5893CCDE72AE4A2" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3E65C51F687AE3DA904E52B4DFFF772" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
The distinctions among the three nominal late Toarcian to Aalenian species 
<taxonomicName id="6959335CCBC57C049711D06F93232E72" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. normandica" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="normandica">
<emphasis id="9788F717D3D19C5CCD903EA29BB4816B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. normandica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9A9767EE39D87A81BD2A00970AB2420A" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. curvisulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="DF1A9CF048E59D75DFBA8627987558AF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="1E3556EC98D37C9A2C208806870CD06A" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. kremmeldorfensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kremmeldorfensis">
<emphasis id="09F859A8CFBE18F2436051431E692C95" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. kremmeldorfensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are all very subtle and it is possible that with more material becoming available from this time interval their nature and validity may have to be revised again. This is also because most specimens so far known from 
<taxonomicName id="000EAE6BA0DD1A4BFE104978847BF540" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. curvisulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="8EB86481EAF6CA1C48B921FF64C5A0CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7C3A8B48B4008D2E49C4152B273BCDF9" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. kremmeldorfensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kremmeldorfensis">
<emphasis id="838768C3DCEEC4B919F40FC22B4EB1F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. kremmeldorfensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are smaller than 1.5 mm in length and, therefore, cannot be considered morphologically mature. 
<bibRefCitation id="9427109AA29FEC72CF57E5C9504DF9A8" author="Schroeder, G" journalOrPublisher="Geologische Blaetter fuer Nordost-Bayern und angrenzende Gebiete" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" pagination="128 - 153" refId="B29" refString="Schroeder, G, 1956. Otolithen aus dem Lias und Dogger des Fraenkischen Jura. Geologische Blaetter fuer Nordost-Bayern und angrenzende Gebiete 6: 128 - 153" title="Otolithen aus dem Lias und Dogger des Fraenkischen Jura." volume="6" year="1956">
<normalizedToken id="1F2C1CD73E2FFDCDCA1760205EC1AC92" originalValue="Schröder">Schroeder</normalizedToken>
(1956)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that the slightly curved shape of the sulcus (cauda) is a distinctive character of the species (hence the name curvisulcatus). However, this character does not seem to be reliable for its distinction from otoliths of 
<taxonomicName id="3D734DFB6EFE409C3AE97DB530DFF912" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. normandica" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="normandica">
<emphasis id="F34EC53BA137EB24D90C5C9ADDB47507" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. normandica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and we therefore consider it to reflect a degree of variability.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="27A24FF85885FDFEB8234B3403A36A2C" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">
The best-preserved and largest specimen that we attribute to 
<taxonomicName id="77D5A6A22A7A68951924AC0D4D6D483A" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. curvisulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="BB574996A6A3D1BF2E1DC63D0E0E02C7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a paratype of 
<normalizedToken id="0F4BBBA37458DED51BD9B092599D15AD" originalValue="Schröder’s">Schroeder's</normalizedToken>
<taxonomicName id="62FF085DF711DB6ED7D42FCBDB7C9B49" authority="Koken, 1884" authorityName="Koken" authorityYear="1884" class="Actinopterygii" family="Leptolepididae" genus="Otolithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Otolithus opalini" order="Elopiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="opalini">
<emphasis id="C1C74CB807278BC23BCBC404B1B2BEAC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">Otolithus opalini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 2.55 mm in length (Plate 
<figureCitation id="2C53334276391A034E0E6AE27D21D24E" captionStart="Plate 1" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Plate 1. Otoliths of Leptolepis normandica and L. curvisulcatus. figs 1 - 15: Leptolepis normandica Nybelin, 1962; 1 - 11: From late Pliensbachian of Buttenheim, 1 - 8, 11: EPH horizon (SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 3); 9: &quot; Quellhorizon &quot; (SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 2); 10: Apyrenum subzone (SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 1); 12: paratype of Ot. cristatus Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 5); 13: paratype of Ot. opalini Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 20); 14: paratype of Ot. vastus Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmelsdorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 34); 15: holotype of Ot. vastus from Peulendorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 30). figs 15 - 19 Leptolepis curvisulcatus (Schroeder, 1956); 15: paratype of Ot. opalini Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 17); 16: holotype of Ot. curvisulcatus Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 42); 17: holotype of Ot. schattenbergi Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmelsdorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 2); 18: paratype of Ot. schattenbergi Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmelsdorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 47); 19: holotype of Ot. opalini Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 16)." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.81737.plate1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671631" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">1</figureCitation>
, fig. 16), while the specimen selected as holotype represents a small and poorly preserved otolith of 1.25 mm in length (Plate 
<figureCitation id="BD26F4BC74162A724006FA07B847CC8B" captionStart="Plate 1" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Plate 1. Otoliths of Leptolepis normandica and L. curvisulcatus. figs 1 - 15: Leptolepis normandica Nybelin, 1962; 1 - 11: From late Pliensbachian of Buttenheim, 1 - 8, 11: EPH horizon (SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 3); 9: &quot; Quellhorizon &quot; (SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 2); 10: Apyrenum subzone (SNSB-BSPG 2022 IV 1); 12: paratype of Ot. cristatus Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 5); 13: paratype of Ot. opalini Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 20); 14: paratype of Ot. vastus Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmelsdorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 34); 15: holotype of Ot. vastus from Peulendorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 30). figs 15 - 19 Leptolepis curvisulcatus (Schroeder, 1956); 15: paratype of Ot. opalini Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 17); 16: holotype of Ot. curvisulcatus Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 42); 17: holotype of Ot. schattenbergi Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmelsdorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 2); 18: paratype of Ot. schattenbergi Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmelsdorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 47); 19: holotype of Ot. opalini Schroeder, 1956 from Kremmeldorf (SNSB-BSPG 2022 III 16)." figureDoi="10.3897/zitteliana.96.81737.plate1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671631" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">1</figureCitation>
, fig. 19). The holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="883B40A2ABCEBE3511E7AD260F118595" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. curvisulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="0FFCFB60B67DA7131CD41619BF7CD6CB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the next best-preserved specimen of 2.25 mm in length, and we have thus chosen this name to represent this nominal species. 
<bibRefCitation id="A22F33DB6758A07FCFD63F88AD2E2691" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/njgpa/2018/0707" author="Schwarzhans, W" journalOrPublisher="Neues Jahrbuch Geologie und Palaeontologie Abhandlungen" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" pagination="75 - 121" refId="B32" refString="Schwarzhans, W, 2018. A review of Jurassic and Early Cretaceous otoliths and the development of early morphological diversity in otoliths. Neues Jahrbuch Geologie und Palaeontologie Abhandlungen 287: 75 - 121, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/njgpa/2018/0707" title="A review of Jurassic and Early Cretaceous otoliths and the development of early morphological diversity in otoliths." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/njgpa/2018/0707" volume="287" year="2018">Schwarzhans (2018)</bibRefCitation>
could not review 
<normalizedToken id="C1092544B00864FA096FE412209A99E1" originalValue="Schröder’s">Schroeder's</normalizedToken>
specimens and attributed similar specimens from the same stratigraphic interval to 
<taxonomicName id="8F81C6566B57444060AF138B4C60C2B4" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. ornatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis id="440CA187D66969EEED54EB859B30B520" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Weiler, 1953). Unfortunately, 
<normalizedToken id="F2E35E3DD808D46B6E645D33918CCDEB" originalValue="Weiler’s">Weiler's</normalizedToken>
type-material has not been located and is not available for revision. His documentation is rather indistinct, so we therefore propose no longer using this name and instead refer to 
<taxonomicName id="B24886F49B4FDC459F1E7036C1D975E4" class="Actinopterygii" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. curvisulcatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="51" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curvisulcatus">
<emphasis id="9925BDDCEEEAB1072A678F22DF9AB167" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="51">L. curvisulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
